    <section class="essay-body">

      <p>Most public discussions about artificial intelligence and work are framed around disappearance: which jobs will be automated and which professions will vanish. That framing assumes a future marketplace shift. It misses what is already happening inside existing roles.</p>

      <p>Many organizations have not eliminated jobs, but they have introduced new tools that supplement those jobs, changing the interior structure of work. What can be expected of the same role is now expanded, while the organizational position of the role remains largely intact.</p>

      <p>This is a subtle shift, with roles carrying more than they were originally designed to hold, though not an increase in difficulty or skill. It’s about volume and simultaneity: more inputs, more options, and more moments that require attention, all within the same temporal and organizational frame under which the role was once designed.</p>

      <p>Just as tools assist with production, they also assist with analysis. Role-defined authority and responsibility remain structurally visible, but beneath more efficient tools, judgment becomes harder to locate. This misalignment obscures where decisions are being made and who is now accountable for them.</p>

      <p>When roles are asked to carry more than they were designed to hold, strain accumulates across the system. When responsibility and judgment remain anchored to structures that no longer match the work being done inside them, it undermines the very authority the system was meant to uphold. Because both the increase in load and the displacement of responsibility occur internally, the resulting misalignment is often misread as an issue of adaptation rather than design.</p>

      <p>Capacity, in this context, refers to what a role can absorb without distorting judgment, timing, or responsibility. It is a property of roles before it belongs to the people who fill them.</p>

      <p>A role has capacity when it can absorb demand without degrading how decisions are made or sequenced. When that capacity exists, there is a margin that allows additional inputs to be evaluated, deferred, or declined without constant interaction.</p>

      <p>Typical work has been operating close to this margin for some time. Many roles already combine execution, coordination, interpretation, and escalation within a single position.</p>

      <p>When capacity is exceeded, roles do not break explicitly. They continue to function with reduced coherence. Attention fragments. Decisions become reactive. The result is the role no longer holds the work in the way it was designed to.</p>

      <p>The effect of AI on capacity is often described in terms of efficiency. Tasks take less time and outputs arrive more quickly. From the outside, this looks like leverage. Inside roles, however, there is a pressure that moves in a different direction.</p>

      <p>AI increases load primarily by expanding the amount of work that enters a role within the same span of time. What follows is increased productivity, and expectations that adjust accordingly and quietly. The same role now reviews more drafts, considers more scenarios, and processes more material within the same timeframe. What was once intermittent becomes continuous.</p>

      <p>This increase is not only a matter of quantity. It is also temporal. As tools shorten the distance between input and response, judgment and decisions cluster more tightly together. Work that once unfolded across days or meetings now arrives in overlapping bursts, leaving fewer natural pauses in which to assess, defer, or decline, and fewer pauses in which to process, decide, and act.</p>

      <p>As AI accelerates production, responsibility and judgment remain assigned as before. Outputs arrive already shaped and authoritative, without corresponding clarity about who exercised judgment in producing them or who carries accountability for them.</p>

      <p>None of this is individually destabilizing, but it changes the interior conditions of work. Roles receive more inputs, faster, and with fewer stopping points. Capacity is eroded as throughput replaces deliberation and accumulation overrides sequence.</p>

      <p>When strain appears under these conditions, it rarely presents as a breaking point. Work continues and deadlines are met. What changes is the internal experience of the role: decisions feel heavier, attention fragments more easily, and the margin for error narrows.</p>

      <p>Because these effects show up inside individual roles, they are often interpreted at the level of the individual. Fatigue and errors are attributed to skill gaps or lack of adaptation.</p>

      <p>This interpretation is reinforced by how organizations measure performance. Output remains legible; internal load does not. Organizations can see what is produced, but not how many simultaneous demands were absorbed to produce it or how much judgment was exercised under compression. As long as work continues to move, structural overload remains.</p>

      <p>This creates a quiet inversion. Roles that are exceeding their designed capacity are treated as if they are underperforming. Tools are applied to improve efficiency or responsiveness, increasing load without addressing its placement. The strain itself is the signal that the structure of the role no longer matches the demands placed upon it.</p>

      <p>This misreading persists not because it is malicious, but because it is convenient. Personal explanations are easier to apply than structural ones. This allows work to continue without questioning how responsibility, timing, and judgment are distributed. The strain remains, but its source stays unexamined.</p>

      <p>Even when this becomes common, organizations continue to function, and from the outside appear sustained.</p>

      <p>What changes is the quality of judgment exercised within the system, which becomes more reactive as roles operate closer to their limits. Because the degradation is gradual, it persists. Performance metrics remain intact. Each instance seems manageable on its own, yet taken together, they reflect a system that is absorbing strain rather than correcting it.</p>

      <p>Over time, this produces a specific kind of fragility. One of dependency on constant throughput to maintain coherence. To the point that deliberation feels inefficient. Judgment is exercised under compression so consistently that it is no longer recognized as judgment.</p>

      <p>The result is not collapse, but drift. So, work continues with diminishing margins and capacity is consumed quietly. The cost is paid later—often somewhere else, by someone else, and without a clear point of origin.</p>

